Modeling and prediction for movies

Setup

Load packages

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(statsr)

Load data

load("movies.Rdata")

Part 1: Data

The data set is comprised of 651 randomly sampled movies produced and released before 2016. Since random sampling is used for data collection the associations and relations observed in the sample can be generalized to the population at large There is no random assignment so no causal relationship can be determined from this sample

Part 2: Research question

Is there an association between audience rating and genre of the movie?

This is an interesting question since at the end of the day commercial success of the movie depends on the audience, which can be best represented by audience score

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

As we can see the distribution is not normal. In order to apply any inferential technique when distribution is not exactly normal we need minimum 30 observations for all levels of a categorical variable

#All genres with entries more than 30
movies %>%
  filter(!is.na(genre) & !is.na(audience_score)) %>%
  group_by(genre) %>%
  summarise(cnt=n()) %>% 
  filter(cnt>30)
## # A tibble: 5 × 2

#Removing genres with very less number of entries
Genre_rat<-movies %>%
  filter(!is.na(genre) & !is.na(imdb_rating) & (genre=="Action & Adventure" 
        |  genre=="Drama" |   genre=="Mystery & Suspense"                                 
         | genre=="Comedy" | genre=="Documentary") )

Genre_rat$genre <- factor(Genre_rat$genre)

We keep only those genres which have number of observation more than 30 in a new data frame and check the mean audience rating for these levels of genre

Genre_rat %>%
  filter(!is.na(genre) & !is.na(audience_score)) %>%
  group_by(genre) %>%
  summarise(avg_rating=mean(audience_score))

## 4              Drama   65.34754
## 5 Mystery & Suspense   55.94915

We can use ANOVA to answer the question that whether difference in mean among the genres that we just saw is statistically significant by using the null hypothesis that there is no difference between mean across genres

However we will need to first verify the conditions require for ANOVA

1.Independence:

a.Within Groups: Since this a random sample it can be said that every successive observation in the sample is independent of the previous observation

  1. Among groups: Secondly,different genres are independent of each other it implies the independence among the groups

2.Normality

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
qqnorm(Genre_rat$imdb_rating[Genre_rat$genre == "Mystery & Suspense"], 
       main = "Documentary rating")
qqline(Genre_rat$imdb_rating[Genre_rat$genre == "Mystery & Suspense"], 
       col = 'blue')

qqnorm(Genre_rat$imdb_rating[Genre_rat$genre == "Action & Adventure"], 
       main = "Action & Adventure rating")
qqline(Genre_rat$imdb_rating[Genre_rat$genre == "Action & Adventure"], 
       col = 'blue')

qqnorm(Genre_rat$imdb_rating[Genre_rat$genre == "Drama"], 
       main = "Drama rating")
qqline(Genre_rat$imdb_rating[Genre_rat$genre == "Drama"], 
       col = 'blue')

qqnorm(Genre_rat$imdb_rating[Genre_rat$genre == "Comedy"], 
       main = "Comedy rating")
qqline(Genre_rat$imdb_rating[Genre_rat$genre == "Comedy"], 
       col = 'blue')

As we can see all the plots are close to the normal line and any skewness can mitigated since each group is of size greater than 30

3.Equal variance among group

ggplot(data=Genre_rat,aes(x=genre,y=audience_score)) +geom_boxplot()+
  ggtitle("Genre and audience score") +
  labs(y="audience score")

As can be seen except documentary every other genre have almost same variability So we can use ANOVA to answer our question that whether average audience score statistically differs across genre

inference(y =audience_score,x = genre, data =Genre_rat,statistic = "mean",
type = "ht",null = 0, alternative = "greater",method = "theoretical") 
## Warning: Ignoring null value since it's undefined for ANOVA

With an overall p-value of less than 0.0001 we can answer the research question that:

“Mean audience score does indeed statistically differ across genre”"

This apply for all pairwise combination of genre except Combination of Action & Adventure,Mystery & Suspense & comedy which can be explained since in real world generally thriller movies do have action in them

As we can see the day,month and year variable for both theatre and dvd release are numeric while it should be a factor since all of them are categorical variable. So, converting all of them to factor

movies$thtr_rel_year<-as.factor(movies$thtr_rel_year)
movies$thtr_rel_month<-as.factor(movies$thtr_rel_month)
movies$thtr_rel_day<-as.factor(movies$thtr_rel_day)
movies$dvd_rel_day<-as.factor(movies$dvd_rel_day)
movies$dvd_rel_month<-as.factor(movies$dvd_rel_month)
movies$dvd_rel_year<-as.factor(movies$dvd_rel_year)

First we will create a new variable weekday variable which contains the day of movie or dvd release since release day may also affect the movie ratings

#creating weekday variable for theatre release
movies$thtr_rel_date <- as.Date(with(movies, paste(thtr_rel_year, 
                                                   thtr_rel_month, thtr_rel_day,sep="-")), "%Y-%m-%d")

movies$thtr_weekday<-weekdays(as.Date(movies$thtr_rel_date,"%Y-%m-%d"))
movies$thtr_weekday<-as.factor(movies$thtr_weekday)

#creating weekday variable for theatre release
movies$dvd_rel_date <- as.Date(with(movies, paste(dvd_rel_year, 
                                                   dvd_rel_month, dvd_rel_day,sep="-")), "%Y-%m-%d")

movies$dvd_weekday<-weekdays(as.Date(movies$dvd_rel_date,"%Y-%m-%d"))
movies$dvd_weekday<-as.factor(movies$dvd_weekday)

Now we clean current data set to remove the variables which are irrelevant/can’t be used for creation of model like:

  1. Name of the movie since each movie has unique name and no relationship can be established using it

2.Year of theatre and dvd release: Since this variable if present in model will not be able to predict for any level which is not present in the dataset like year 2016 which will be the case for the latest movies

3.Best picture nomination and win: For the latest movies oscar nominations have not been announced hence there can be no conclusive yes or no value for this variable

4.Removing actor one to five : Same reason as second. An actor/actress not present in data set will not give result when use for prediction

# Removing all irrelevant variables as mentioned above

movies<-movies[,-c(1,7,10,19,20,25:32,33,35)]

As we can see from the model result genre is indeed a significant predictor for audience score but it is able to explain only 18% variability in audience score.

Hence we need other variables which can explain variability in audience score more significantly

So we will use forward selection technique based on the adjusted R square to predict the audience score

We are using adjusted square since it shows the variability in response variable explained by predictors after penalising for adding new variables rather than using the P value approach since p value :

1.Just shows the significant predictors 2.Uses 5% significance level which is arbitrary and change of significance level will lead to change of model

Adding all variables one by one to determine the first variable to be added to the model based on highest adjusted R square

  filter(is.na(studio)==F) 

# since imdb_rating is the only explanatory variable
plot(m_final$residuals ~ movies$imdb_rating)

Since there is no pattern in distribution of residuals condition for linearity is established

  1. Normality
hist(m_final$residuals)

qqnorm(m_final$residuals)

Since histogram is nearly normal with mean at 0 condition of noramlity is satisfied

3.Constant variability of residuals

plot(m_final$residuals ~ m_final$fitted.values)

Since there is no pattern in distirbution of residuals the condition of constant variability is met

  1. Independence:
plot(m_final$residuals)

So conditon of independence is met since distribution is random

1.Average audience rating of genres like Action & Adventure,Animation,Art House & International,Comedy is very high compared to critics rating. Documentary and Musical movies are liked heavily by audience and critics alike
